    edibility: "toxic",
    toxicityNotes: "Moderately poisonous, especially if eaten raw, known to cause violent gastroenteritis. Symptoms are predominantly gastrointestinal: nausea, abdominal pain, and violent vomiting with bloody diarrhea lasting up to six hours. The toxic enzyme bolesatine, a protein synthesis inhibitor that causes massive thrombosis in mice and acts as a mitogen at lower concentrations, has been isolated from the fruiting bodies and is implicated in the poisonings. Muscarine has also been isolated but in quantities believed too small to cause toxic effects in humans. Recent studies associate poisoning with hyperprocalcitonemia, classified as a distinct fungal-poisoning syndrome.",
