    substrate: "On the ground, fruiting singly or in clusters; forms an ectomycorrhizal sheath around pine roots and a Hartig net between the outer root cells, exchanging soil-derived nutrients for host carbohydrates. A whitish mycelium at the stipe base helps anchor the fruit body in the substrate.",
    habitat: "An ectomycorrhizal fungus forming symbiotic associations with pines, best known in North America from eastern white pine (Pinus strobus). Fruits on the ground, singly or in clusters, throughout northeastern North America north into Canada and south to Guerrero, Mexico, typically in late summer and autumn (and may appear in relatively dry weather when other mushrooms are scarce). DNA sequencing indicates a much broader Northern Hemisphere distribution, including East Asia and the Balkan Peninsula, where it occurs in high-altitude Macedonian pine forests. Western North American material long reported as the closely related S. sibiricus (associated with Pinus monticola and Pinus flexilis) has been treated as part of the same circumboreal species complex (formalized as S. americanus f. pseudosibiricus).",
